categories.description: Odin is the Allfather of Norse mythology, ruler of Asgard who sacrificed his eye for wisdom at Mimir's well.
Odin appears as Thor's father in Marvel, portrayed by Anthony Hopkins, but originates from Norse mythology.
Odin is Norse, not Greek. The Greek king of the gods is Zeus.
Odin is Norse, not Roman. The Roman king of the gods is Jupiter.
Thor is the Norse god of thunder, son of Odin, wielder of the mighty hammer Mjölnir.
Thor is a founding Avenger in Marvel, but he originates from Norse mythology, not comics.
Thor is Norse, not Greek. The Greek god of thunder is Zeus.
Thor is Norse, not Roman. The Roman god of thunder is Jupiter.
Freya is the Norse goddess of love, beauty, and war who rides a chariot pulled by cats.
Freya is Norse, not Greek. The Greek goddess of love is Aphrodite.
Freya is Norse, not Roman. The Roman goddess of love is Venus.
Týr is the Norse god of war and justice who bravely lost his hand to the wolf Fenrir.
Týr is a Faroese folk metal band known for incorporating Norse mythology into their music.
Tyr is Norse, not Greek. The Greek god of war is Ares.
Tyr is Norse, not Roman. The Roman god of war is Mars.
Baldur is the Norse god of light, purity, and beauty, famously killed by mistletoe through Loki's trickery.
Baldur is Norse, not Greek. The Greek god of light is Apollo.
Heimdall is the Norse guardian of the rainbow bridge Bifröst, possessing sight and hearing across all nine realms.
Heimdall appears in Marvel as the gatekeeper, but he originates from Norse mythology.
Frigg is Odin's wife and the Norse goddess of marriage, motherhood, and foresight.
Frigg is Norse, not Greek. The Greek queen of the gods is Hera.
Frigg is Norse, not Roman. The Roman queen of the gods is Juno.
Hel is the Norse goddess ruling the underworld realm of the dead, daughter of Loki, half alive and half corpse.
Hel is Norse, not Greek. The Greek underworld is ruled by Hades, not Hel.
Hel is Norse, not Roman. The Roman underworld is ruled by Pluto.
Fenrir is the monstrous Norse wolf, son of Loki, prophesied to kill Odin during Ragnarök.
Fenrir is the name of multiple metal bands inspired by Norse mythology.
Fenrir appears as a Beast-Warrior type card in Yu-Gi-Oh! based on Norse mythology.
While not an official D&D creature, Fenrir-inspired giant wolves frequently appear in Norse-themed campaigns.
Zeus is the king of the Greek gods, ruler of Mount Olympus, wielder of lightning bolts.
Zeus is Greek, not Roman. The Roman equivalent is Jupiter.
Zeus is Greek, not Norse. The Norse king of the gods is Odin (though Thor wields thunder).
Apollo is the Greek god of the sun, music, poetry, prophecy, and healing.
Apollo is one of the few gods who kept the same name in Roman mythology, honored equally by both cultures.
Apollo GraphQL is a popular framework for building GraphQL APIs and managing data.
The Buick Apollo was a compact car produced in the 1970s.
NASA's Apollo program (1961-1972) achieved the first human Moon landings, including Apollo 11 in 1969.
Athena is the Greek goddess of wisdom, warfare, and crafts, born fully armored from Zeus's head.
AWS Athena is Amazon's serverless interactive query service for analyzing data in S3 using SQL.
Athena is Greek, not Roman. The Roman equivalent is Minerva.
Poseidon is the Greek god of the sea, earthquakes, and horses, wielding a mighty trident.
Poseidon is Greek, not Roman. The Roman equivalent is Neptune.
Hades is the Greek god of the underworld, ruler of the dead and keeper of the souls.
Hades is Greek, not Roman. The Roman equivalent is Pluto.
Ares is the Greek god of war, representing the violent and brutal aspects of warfare.
Ares appears as Wonder Woman's enemy in DC Comics, but he originates from Greek mythology.
Ares is Greek, not Roman. The Roman equivalent is Mars.
Hercules (Greek: Heracles) is the legendary demigod son of Zeus, famous for completing the Twelve Labors.
Marvel's Hercules has been a hero since the 1960s, but he originates from Greek/Roman mythology.
Hercules is actually the Roman name; the Greek original is Heracles. Both refer to the same legendary hero.
Hermes is the Greek messenger god, patron of travelers, thieves, and commerce, wearing winged sandals.
Hermes is Facebook's JavaScript engine optimized for React Native mobile applications.
Hermes is Greek, not Roman. The Roman equivalent is Mercury.
Artemis is the Greek goddess of the hunt, wilderness, and the moon, Apollo's twin sister.
NASA's Artemis program aims to return humans to the Moon - the mythological sequel to Apollo we needed.
Artemis is Greek, not Roman. The Roman equivalent is Diana.
Aphrodite is the Greek goddess of love, beauty, and desire, born from sea foam.
Aphrodite is Greek, not Roman. The Roman equivalent is Venus.
Dionysus is the Greek god of wine, festivity, theater, and religious ecstasy.
Dionysus is Greek, not Roman. The Roman equivalent is Bacchus.
Atlas is the Greek Titan condemned to hold up the sky for eternity as punishment from Zeus.
MongoDB Atlas is a cloud-hosted database service for deploying and managing MongoDB databases.
The Volkswagen Atlas is a three-row midsize SUV introduced in 2017.
Atlas is a moon of Saturn discovered in 1980, shaped like a flying saucer due to equatorial ridge.
The Atlas rocket family has launched countless satellites and Moon missions since the 1950s.
Atlas appears in Marvel and DC Comics, but the character is based on the Greek mythological Titan.
Atlas is Greek, not Roman. The Romans adopted Greek Titans but Atlas kept his Greek name.
Pegasus is the divine winged horse born from Medusa's blood when Perseus beheaded her.
Pegasus is an air-launched rocket system that deploys satellites from aircraft.
Pegasus is a prominent constellation in the northern sky, depicting the winged horse.
Pegasus is Greek, not Roman, though Romans adopted the myth. The creature originated in Greek mythology.
Centaurs are Greek mythological creatures with the upper body of a human and lower body of a horse.
Centaur is a rocket upper stage, the first to use liquid hydrogen fuel, used since the 1960s.
Centaurs are a playable race in D&D, but they originate from Greek mythology.
Centaurs appear frequently in Magic: The Gathering, especially in Theros (Greek-inspired) sets.
Centaurs are a class of minor planets orbiting between Jupiter and Neptune, named after the mythical creatures.
Psyche is the Greek personification of the soul who married Eros after completing Venus's trials.
NASA's Psyche mission (arriving 2029) will explore the metal-rich asteroid that may be a planetary core.
16 Psyche is a massive metal-rich asteroid in the main belt, possibly the exposed core of a protoplanet.
Gemini means 'the twins' in Greek, referring to the mythological brothers Castor and Pollux.
NASA's Gemini program (1961-1966) used two-astronaut spacecraft to develop techniques for Apollo Moon missions.
Gemini is a zodiac constellation representing the twins Castor and Pollux.
Gemini was a pop duo, not a rock band. Don't confuse musical genres.
Cassandra was a Trojan princess cursed by Apollo to speak true prophecies that no one would believe.
Apache Cassandra is a distributed NoSQL database designed for handling massive amounts of data.
Pandora opened the forbidden box releasing all evils into the world, leaving only hope inside.
Pandora is a music streaming and automated recommendation service founded in 2000.
Pandora is a small moon of Saturn with an irregular shape, discovered in 1980.
Jupiter is the Roman king of the gods, ruler of the sky and thunder, equivalent to Greek Zeus.
Jupiter is the largest planet in our solar system, a gas giant with the Great Red Spot storm.
Jupiter is Roman, not Greek. The Greek equivalent is Zeus.
Mars is the Roman god of war, father of Romulus and Remus, founders of Rome.
Mars is the 'Red Planet', the fourth planet from the Sun with two small moons.
Mars Black, Mars Red, and Mars Yellow are iron oxide pigments used in painting.
Mars is Roman, not Greek. The Greek equivalent is Ares.
Venus is the Roman goddess of love, beauty, and desire, mother of Cupid.
Venus is the second planet from the Sun, the brightest natural object in Earth's night sky after the Moon.
Venus is Roman, not Greek. The Greek equivalent is Aphrodite.
Neptune is the Roman god of the sea, earthquakes, and horses, wielding a trident.
Neptune is the eighth planet from the Sun, an ice giant with supersonic winds.
Neptune is Roman, not Greek. The Greek equivalent is Poseidon.
Mercury is the Roman messenger god, patron of commerce, travelers, and thieves.
Mercury is the smallest planet and closest to the Sun, with extreme temperature variations.
Project Mercury (1958-1963) was NASA's first human spaceflight program, putting Americans in orbit.
Mercury was Ford's mid-luxury car brand that operated from 1938 to 2011.
Mercury is Roman, not Greek. The Greek equivalent is Hermes.
Vulcan is the Roman god of fire, metalworking, and the forge, equivalent to Greek Hephaestus.
ULA's Vulcan Centaur is a commercial launch vehicle, not a NASA mission or spacecraft.
Minerva is the Roman goddess of wisdom, strategic warfare, and crafts, equivalent to Greek Athena.
Juno is the Roman queen of the gods, protector of marriage and women, Jupiter's wife.
Juno was OpenStack's code name for the 2014.2 release of the cloud computing platform.
NASA's Juno spacecraft has orbited Jupiter since 2016 - who better to peer through the clouds and see what Jupiter is up to?
Ceres is the Roman goddess of agriculture, grain, and the harvest.
Ceres is the largest object in the asteroid belt, classified as a dwarf planet since 2006.
Pluto is the Roman god of the underworld and wealth beneath the earth, equivalent to Greek Hades.
Pluto is a dwarf planet in the Kuiper belt, famously reclassified from full planet status in 2006.
The Morrígan is the Celtic goddess of war, fate, and death, often appearing as a crow on battlefields.
Morrigan is Celtic, not Norse. Norse war deities include Odin and the Valkyries.
Morrigan is Celtic, not Greek. Greek war deities include Ares and Athena.
Brigid is the Celtic goddess of fire, poetry, healing, and smithcraft, honored at Imbolc.
Brigid is Celtic, not Norse. Norse fire/smith associations include the dwarves.
Brigid is Celtic, not Greek. The Greek goddess with similar domains is Athena (crafts) and Hephaestus (smithing).
Cernunnos is the Celtic horned god of nature, animals, fertility, and the wilderness.
Cernunnos is Celtic, not Greek. The Greek nature god is Pan (also horned).
Cernunnos appears in D&D's Celtic pantheon, but he originates from Celtic mythology.
Danu is the Celtic mother goddess and ancestor of the Tuatha Dé Danann tribe of gods.
Lugh is the Celtic god of craftsmanship, skill, and many talents, honored at Lughnasadh.
Lugh is Celtic, not Norse. Don't confuse with the Norse trickster Loki despite similar sounds.
Lugh appears in D&D's Celtic pantheon, but he originates from Celtic mythology.
The Dagda is the Celtic father god wielding a magic club and owning a cauldron of plenty.
Sounds like Dagobah, Yoda's swamp planet, but the Dagda is a Celtic god with a magic club, not a Force-wielding hermit.
Epona is the Celtic goddess of horses, fertility, and the protector of riders.
Link's horse Epona is named after the Celtic goddess, but is a video game character, not the deity herself.
Epona was one of the few Celtic deities adopted into Roman worship, especially by cavalry units.
Epona is Celtic, not Greek. Greek horse associations include Poseidon and the Centaurs.
Daedalus is the Greek mythological master craftsman, inventor of the Labyrinth and wax wings, father of Icarus.
Daedalus is the official cryptocurrency wallet for Cardano blockchain, naturally named after a mythical inventor.
Triton is the Greek merman god, messenger of the sea, son of Poseidon.
Triton is NVIDIA's GPU programming language and inference server for deploying AI models.
Tritons are a playable race in D&D, but they originate from Greek mythology.
Triton is Neptune's largest moon, the only large moon with a retrograde orbit.
Triton is Greek, not Roman, though he was adopted into Roman mythology under the same name.
Medusa is the Greek Gorgon with snake hair whose gaze turns people to stone, slain by Perseus.
Medusa is an open-source headless commerce platform built with Node.js.
Medusas are classic D&D monsters with petrifying gaze, but they originate from Greek mythology.
Marvel's Medusa (Queen of Inhumans) is a different character - she has living hair, not snakes, and isn't based on the Greek myth.
Gorgons appear in Magic: The Gathering, inspired by Medusa and Greek mythology.
Cerberus is the three-headed dog guarding the gates of the Greek underworld, preventing escape.
Cerberus was a popular Android anti-theft and security app (discontinued 2019).
Cerberus appears in D&D's Nine Hells, but originates from Greek mythology.
While Romans adopted Cerberus into their mythology, the creature originated in Greek myth.
Hyperion is the Greek Titan of light and father of the sun god Helios.
Apache Hyperion is an OLAP server for multidimensional data analysis.
Hyperion is an irregularly shaped moon of Saturn with a sponge-like appearance.
Marvel's Hyperion is a Superman pastiche, not based on the Greek Titan despite sharing the name.
Chronos is the Greek personification of Time itself, often confused with the Titan Kronos.
Chronos is a distributed cron job scheduler developed by Airbnb for Mesos.
Morpheus is the Greek god of dreams, son of Hypnos, who can shape-shift and appear in dreams.
Morpheus is NVIDIA's cybersecurity AI framework for detecting and preventing threats.
DC's Sandman (Morpheus) is inspired by but distinct from the Greek god of dreams.
Talos is the Greek mythological bronze automaton giant who protected Crete from invaders.
Talos is Cisco's threat intelligence organization providing security research.
Marvel's Talos is a Skrull alien, not related to the Greek bronze giant despite sharing the name.
Helios is the Greek Titan god of the Sun who drives his chariot across the sky each day.
Helios is LinkedIn's search and indexing platform for powering search functionality.
Helios is another name for the Sun itself in astronomical and scientific contexts.
Hera is the Greek queen of the gods, goddess of marriage and family, Zeus's wife.
Hera is a Python SDK for orchestrating workflows on Argo, a Kubernetes workflow engine.
Hera is Greek, not Roman. The Roman equivalent is Juno.
The Kraken is a legendary Norse sea monster of enormous size that drags ships to the depths.
Kraken is a major cryptocurrency exchange and also Kraken.js, a Node.js framework by PayPal.
The Kraken is a powerful D&D monster, but it originates from Norse/Scandinavian folklore.
Despite appearing in Clash of the Titans, the Kraken is Norse, not Greek. Greek sea monsters include Scylla and Charybdis.
Krakens appear in Magic: The Gathering as powerful blue creatures, inspired by Norse mythology.
Icarus is the Greek figure who flew too close to the sun on wax wings, causing his tragic fall.
Icarus Verilog is an open-source hardware simulation and synthesis tool for digital circuits.
The Titans are the primordial Greek gods who preceded the Olympians, overthrown by Zeus.
Titan is Google's Tensor Processing Unit (TPU) for AI and machine learning workloads.
The Nissan Titan is a full-size pickup truck competing with Ford F-150 and Chevy Silverado.
Titan is Saturn's largest moon with liquid methane lakes - the only moon with a dense atmosphere.
The Titan rocket family was a major launch vehicle series from the 1950s through 2005.
DC's Teen Titans are named after the Greek mythological beings, though the heroes themselves are original.
Titans are colossal war machines in Warhammer 40,000, the largest combat units of the Adeptus Titanicus.
Sleipnir is Odin's eight-legged horse in Norse mythology, the fastest steed in all nine realms.
Sleipnir was a Japanese web browser known for its tab features and customization options.
Lambda (λ) is the 11th letter of the Greek alphabet.
Lambda is a core concept in functional programming representing anonymous functions (lambda calculus).
AWS Lambda is Amazon's serverless computing service for running code without managing servers.
Alpha (α) is the first letter of the Greek alphabet, symbolizing beginning or first position.
Alpha refers to early software testing phases and Alphabet Inc., Google's parent company.
Alpha is tech culture jargon for early access, prototype releases, and startup culture terminology.
Alfa Romeo is the Italian luxury sports car brand (note the spelling: Alfa, not Alpha).
Beta (β) is the second letter of the Greek alphabet.
Beta is the pre-release software testing phase where limited users test for bugs.
Beta testing and 'beta release' are fundamental concepts in software development cycles.
Beta culture permeates Silicon Valley with perpetual beta products and 'fail fast' mentality.
Delta (δ, Δ) is the fourth letter of the Greek alphabet, often representing change in mathematics.
The Lancia Delta is an iconic rally car that dominated the World Rally Championship.
Delta is used in tech for version control, differential updates, and change tracking systems.
Delta represents difference or change in mathematics, physics, and computer science.
Omega (Ω) is the 24th and final letter of the Greek alphabet, symbolizing 'the end'.
The Oldsmobile Omega was a compact car produced from 1973 to 1984.
Omega appears in various tech products including Omega watches' precision engineering.
Omega is a Hungarian progressive rock band formed in the 1960s.
Sigma (Σ, σ) is the 18th letter of the Greek alphabet, used to denote summation in mathematics.
Sigma includes Six Sigma quality methodology and Sigma camera/lens brand.
Sigma represents summation in math and statistics, and spawned the 'sigma male' internet meme.
Pi (π) is the 16th letter of the Greek alphabet.
The Raspberry Pi is a revolutionary single-board computer that democratized DIY electronics.
Pi represents the mathematical constant 3.14159... fundamental to computing and mathematics.
Tau (τ) is the 19th letter of the Greek alphabet.
The Tau Empire in Warhammer 40,000 uses the Greek letter's name but is an original sci-fi faction, not based on mythology.
Tau represents 2π (6.28...), advocated by some mathematicians as superior to pi for circular mathematics.
Tau is a Greek letter, not a deity or figure from Greek mythology.
Kappa (κ) is the 10th letter of the Greek alphabet.
Kappa is the famous Twitch emote (the grey face) used to denote sarcasm or trolling.
Cohen's kappa coefficient measures inter-rater agreement in statistics and machine learning.
Valkyries are Norse warrior maidens who choose the worthy slain for Odin's hall, Valhalla.
Valkyries appear as celestial warriors in D&D, but they originate from Norse mythology.
The Aston Martin Valkyrie is a limited-production hybrid hypercar developed with Red Bull Racing.
Marvel's Valkyrie is based on the Norse mythological warrior maidens, not an original creation.
Valkyries are Norse, not Greek. Greek female warriors include the Amazons.
Valkyries appear in Magic: The Gathering's Kaldheim set, inspired by Norse mythology.
Mjolnir is Thor's mighty hammer in Norse mythology, forged by dwarven brothers Brokkr and Sindri.
Mjolnir appears in Marvel as Thor's hammer, but it originates from Norse mythology.
Mjolnir is Norse, not Greek. The Greek smith god Hephaestus made different legendary items.
Yggdrasil is the immense World Tree in Norse mythology connecting the nine realms.
Yggdrasil was an early Linux distribution and is also a modern mesh network protocol.
World tree concepts inspired by Yggdrasil appear in Magic: The Gathering's Kaldheim set.
Yggdrasil is Norse, not Greek. Greek mythology has no equivalent world tree concept.
Ragnarok is the Norse apocalypse where Odin dies fighting Fenrir and the world is reborn.
Thor: Ragnarok uses the Norse concept, but the mythology predates Marvel by centuries.
Ragnarok is Norse, not Greek. The Greek apocalypse concept differs entirely.
Asgard is the heavenly realm of the Norse gods, connected to Midgard by the rainbow bridge Bifröst.
Asgard appears in Marvel as Thor's home realm, but it originates from Norse mythology.
Asgard is Norse, not Greek. The Greek gods resided on Mount Olympus.
Bifröst is the burning rainbow bridge connecting Asgard to Midgard in Norse mythology.
Bifrost is a remote access tool and identity-aware proxy for cloud infrastructure.
The Bifrost appears in Marvel's Thor films, but it originates from Norse mythology.
Valhalla is the Norse hall of the slain in Asgard where warriors who die in battle feast with Odin.
Valhalla features in Marvel's Thor comics, but it originates from Norse mythology.
Assassin's Creed Valhalla uses the Norse concept, but Valhalla itself is mythology, not a game creation.
Valhalla is Norse, not Greek. The Greek afterlife realms include Elysium and the Underworld.
Jormungandr is the Midgard Serpent in Norse myth, so large it encircles the entire world.
Jormungandr appears in D&D as a colossal serpent, but it originates from Norse mythology.
Jormungandr is Norse, not Greek. Greek serpent monsters include Python and the Hydra.
While 'World Serpent' sounds like a Smash character, Jormungandr is a Norse mythological creature, not a video game character.
Bacchus is the Roman god of wine, ecstasy, and ritual madness, equivalent to Greek Dionysus.
Bacchus is Roman, not Greek. The Greek equivalent is Dionysus.
Diana is the Roman goddess of the hunt, moon, and wilderness, equivalent to Greek Artemis.
Wonder Woman's name Diana Prince references the Roman goddess, connecting her to classical mythology.
Diana is Roman, not Greek. The Greek equivalent is Artemis.
Saturn is the Roman god of time, agriculture, and wealth, equivalent to Greek Kronos.
The Sega Saturn was a 32-bit video game console released in 1994.
Saturn is the sixth planet from the Sun, famous for its spectacular ring system.
The Saturn V rocket was the mighty launch vehicle that sent Apollo missions to the Moon.
Saturn was GM's car brand (1985-2010) focused on customer service and no-haggle pricing.
Saturn is Roman, not Greek. The Greek equivalent is Kronos (Cronus), the Titan father of Zeus.
Cupid is the Roman god of love and desire, often depicted as a winged child with bow and arrows.
Cupid is Roman, not Greek. The Greek equivalent is Eros.
Flora is the Roman goddess of flowers, spring, and the renewal of nature, celebrated during Floralia.
Fortuna is the Roman goddess of fortune, luck, and fate, depicted with the Wheel of Fortune.
Vesta is the Roman goddess of the hearth and home, served by the Vestal Virgins.
The Lada Vesta is a compact car produced by Russian automaker AvtoVAZ since 2015.
Janus is the two-faced Roman god of doorways, beginnings, transitions, and endings - January is named after him.
Janus is uniquely Roman with no Greek equivalent. The Greeks had no comparable two-faced god.
Nuada is the Celtic god-king of the Tuatha Dé Danann who lost his arm in battle and received a silver replacement.
Nuada appears in D&D's Celtic pantheon, but he originates from Celtic mythology.
Nuada is Celtic, not Norse. The Norse god who lost a hand is Tyr (to Fenrir).
Taranis is the Celtic god of thunder and lightning, depicted with a wheel symbolizing the sky.
Taranis is Celtic, not Norse. The Norse god of thunder is Thor.
Taranis is Celtic, not Greek. The Greek god who wields thunder is Zeus.
Taranis is Celtic, not Roman. The Roman thunder god is Jupiter.
Ogma is the Celtic god of eloquence and learning, credited with inventing the Ogham alphabet.
Ogma appears in D&D's Forgotten Realms as a god of knowledge, but he originates from Celtic mythology.
Ogma is Celtic, not Greek. The Greek god of eloquence is Hermes.
Manannán mac Lir is the Celtic god of the sea, guardian of the otherworld, and master of magical items.
Manannán is Celtic, not Greek. The Greek sea god is Poseidon.
Manannán is Celtic, not Norse. Norse sea deities include Njord and Aegir.
Belenus is the Celtic god of the sun, healing, and light, honored at the Beltane festival.
Arianrhod is the Celtic goddess of the moon, stars, and the Silver Wheel (Caer Arianrhod).
Rhiannon is the Welsh goddess associated with horses, birds, and the otherworld.
Rhiannon is a famous Fleetwood Mac song, but the song title doesn't make her a band herself.
Balor is the Celtic one-eyed giant king of the evil Fomorians with a deadly destructive gaze.
D&D's Balor demons are named after the Celtic giant, though they are fiery winged demons, not one-eyed giants.
D&D's Balor demons were originally called Balrogs until Tolkien's estate complained. Balor (Celtic) and Balrog (Tolkien) are different.
Balor is Celtic, not Greek. The Greek one-eyed giants are the Cyclopes.
Sucellos is the Celtic god of agriculture, forests, and alcoholic drinks, wielding a long-handled hammer.
Andraste is the Celtic goddess of victory and war, famously invoked by Queen Boudica before battle.
Mabon is the Welsh divine son and hunter, associated with the autumn equinox harvest festival.
Aengus (Óengus) is the Celtic god of love, youth, and poetic inspiration, son of the Dagda.
The Odyssey is Homer's epic poem chronicling Odysseus's ten-year journey home from the Trojan War.
The Honda Odyssey is a popular family minivan known for reliability and practicality.
Avalon is the mythical island in Arthurian legend where King Arthur was taken to heal after his final battle.
The Toyota Avalon is a full-size sedan positioned as Toyota's flagship luxury car.
Avalon imagery appears in Magic: The Gathering, inspired by Arthurian legend.
Avalon is from Celtic/Arthurian legend, not Greek mythology.
Aurora is the Roman goddess of the dawn who renews herself each morning, equivalent to Greek Eos.
The Oldsmobile Aurora was a luxury sedan produced from 1995 to 2003.
The aurora borealis (northern lights) and aurora australis are spectacular light displays in polar skies.
Marvel's Aurora shares her name with the Roman goddess, though she's a mutant speedster, not the deity.
Aurora is Roman, not Greek. The Greek equivalent is Eos.
Eos is the Greek goddess of the dawn, sister of Helios and Selene.
The Volkswagen Eos was a retractable hardtop convertible produced from 2006 to 2015.
Eos is Greek, not Roman. The Roman equivalent is Aurora.
Phaeton was the mortal son of Helios who crashed the sun chariot, nearly destroying the earth.
The Volkswagen Phaeton was VW's luxury flagship sedan produced from 2002 to 2016.
Electra was a Greek princess in the tragedies of Sophocles and Euripides, daughter of Agamemnon.
The Buick Electra was a luxury car produced from 1959 to 1990.
Marvel's Elektra (spelled with K) draws her name from the Greek figure, though she's an original assassin character.
Electra is one of the Pleiades stars (17 Tauri), named after one of the seven sisters in Greek mythology.
The Plymouth Fury was an iconic muscle car produced from 1955 to 1989.
Nick Fury is Marvel's eye-patched director of SHIELD, master spy and assembler of the Avengers.
While 'The Furies' (Erinyes) are Greek vengeance goddesses, 'Fury' singular is too generic to assume this category.
Orion is one of the most recognizable constellations, featuring Betelgeuse and the distinctive belt.
Orion was a giant huntsman in Greek mythology, placed among the stars by Zeus.
The Ford Orion was a compact sedan sold in Europe from 1983 to 1997.
NASA's Orion is the crew capsule designed for deep space exploration, including Artemis Moon missions.
A nova is a stellar explosion caused by thermonuclear reactions on a white dwarf's surface.
The Chevrolet Nova was a popular compact muscle car produced from 1962 to 1988.
Marvel's Nova Corps is named after the astronomical phenomenon, not based on any mythological figure.
Vega is the fifth-brightest star in the night sky, part of the Summer Triangle asterism.
The Chevrolet Vega was a subcompact car produced from 1970 to 1977.
Vega is AMD's GPU microarchitecture used in Radeon RX graphics cards.
Polaris is the North Star, aligned with Earth's rotational axis, used for navigation for millennia.
Polaris is AMD's GPU architecture from 2016 used in Radeon RX 400 and 500 series.
Polaris is a manufacturer of snowmobiles, ATVs, and off-road vehicles.
Marvel's Polaris is named after the star, not based on any mythological figure.
Sirius is the brightest star in the night sky, known as the 'Dog Star' in Canis Major.
Sirius XM is the satellite radio broadcasting company formed in 2008.
The Andromeda Galaxy (M31) is our nearest large galaxy, on a collision course with the Milky Way.
Andromeda was the Greek princess chained to a rock as sacrifice, rescued by Perseus.
Andromeda is a Swedish progressive death metal band formed in 1999.
The equinoxes occur twice yearly when day and night are approximately equal in length.
The Chevrolet Equinox is a compact crossover SUV introduced in 2004.
The solstices mark the longest and shortest days of the year at summer and winter peaks.
The Pontiac Solstice was a sporty roadster produced from 2006 to 2009.
The solar corona is the Sun's outer atmosphere, visible as a white halo during total eclipses.
The Toyota Corona was a midsize sedan produced from 1957 to 2001.
A pulsar is a rapidly rotating neutron star emitting beams of electromagnetic radiation.
The Nissan Pulsar is a compact car sold globally under various names since 1978.
A quasar is an extremely luminous active galactic nucleus powered by a supermassive black hole.
Quasar is a Vue.js framework for building responsive web applications with a single codebase.
NASA's twin Voyager spacecraft (1977) are the most distant human-made objects, now in interstellar space.
Voyager is an Australian progressive metal band that competed in Eurovision 2023.
The Cassini-Huygens mission studied Saturn for 13 years (1997-2017) before its dramatic finale plunge.
Giovanni Cassini discovered Saturn's moon gaps (Cassini Division) and multiple moons.
NASA's Dawn spacecraft was the first to orbit two extraterrestrial bodies: Vesta (2011) and Ceres (2015).
Dawn explored the 'dawn of the solar system' by studying ancient protoplanets in the asteroid belt.
Comets are icy bodies that develop glowing tails when approaching the Sun.
The Mercury Comet was a compact car produced from 1960 to 1977.
A meteor is a space rock burning up in Earth's atmosphere, creating a 'shooting star'.
Meteor.js is a full-stack JavaScript framework for building real-time web applications.
A nebula is an interstellar cloud of gas and dust where stars are born.
Marvel's Nebula is named after the astronomical term, not based on any mythological figure.
Nebula is an astronomical term (Latin for 'cloud'), not a Greek mythological figure.
Europa is Jupiter's icy moon with a subsurface ocean that may harbor life.
Europa was the Phoenician princess abducted by Zeus disguised as a bull - Europe is named after her.
NASA's Europa Clipper mission (arriving 2030) will study Jupiter's moon for habitability.
Ganymede is the largest moon in the solar system, orbiting Jupiter with its own magnetic field.
Ganymede was the beautiful Trojan prince abducted by Zeus to be cupbearer of the gods.
Callisto is Jupiter's second-largest moon, the most heavily cratered object in the solar system.
Callisto was a nymph transformed into a bear by jealous Hera after Zeus seduced her.
Io is Jupiter's volcanic moon, the most geologically active body in the solar system.
Io was a priestess of Hera transformed into a white cow by Zeus to hide their affair.
